┌─ Summary ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                                                                            │
│  This project provides efficient implementations of various algorithms     │
│  for sampling elements from the general linear group over a finite field.  │
│  The implementations are written in C and rely on FLINT (Fast Library for  │
│  Number Theory) for field arithmetic and linear algebra operations.        │
│                                                                            │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

┌─ Algorithms ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                                                                            │
│  Implementations of the following algorithms to sample from GL(n, q)       │
│  uniformly at random are included.                                         │
│                                                                            │
│    bruhat                                                                  │
│      Algorithm 5.4.3 from [3], based on Bruhat decomposition.              │
│                                                                            │
│    nonsing                                                                 │
│      NonSing algorithm from [1].                                           │
│                                                                            │
│    rej                                                                     │
│      a standard rejection sampling method.                                 │
│                                                                            │
│    schubert                                                                │
│      Algorithm 5.3.2 from [3], based on sampling Schubert cells.           │
│                                                                            │
│    subgroup                                                                │
│      The general subgroup algorithm from [2].                              │
│                                                                            │
│    unrank                                                                  │
│      A novel algorithm based on combinatorial ranking which requires       │
│      only a single integer sampled uniformly at random.                    │
│                                                                            │
│    gs                                                                      │
│      An inlined version of `unrank` based on Gram-Schmidt.                 │
│                                                                            │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

┌─ Usage ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                                                                            │
│  To run the test suite, issue the command `make test`. This will run a     │
│  series of randomized tests for each implemented algorithm.                │
│                                                                            │
│  To run benchmarks, issue the command `make prof`. This will measure the   │
│  amount of time and CPU cycles each algorithm takes to run, for some       │
│  selected parameters used in quantum-safe cryptographic protocols that     │
│  employ invertible matrices.                                               │
│                                                                            │
│  The `test-c` and `prof-c` targets are also available for running tests    │
│  and profiling with a counter for `n_randlimb` calls, using `LD_PRELOAD`.  │
│  This allows measuring the amount of random bits used by each algorithm.   │
│                                                                            │
│  The `CHUNK_SIZE` variable can be used to control the minimum size of a    │
│  word emitted by `n_randlimb`, with buffering implemented via the FDR      │
│  algorithm [4].                                                            │
│                                                                            │
│  The `fmt-table.sh` script can be used to pretty-print tables with ratios  │
│  for CPU cycles and amount of random bits with respect to the ``best''     │
│  algorithm. For instance, issue the command                                │
│                                                                            │
│    sh fmt-table.sh -l                                                      │
│                                                                            │
│  to create a table with information on the amount of limbs.                │
│                                                                            │
└────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

[1] https://doi.org/10.1002/rsa.3240040108
[2] https://doi.org/10.1017/S0269964800000255
[3] https://doi.org/10.1090/dimacs/043/12
[4] https://arxiv.org/abs/1304.1916v1
